4. If --preview reports "No files found" but the path clearly exists, the path is hidden (dotfile) or git-ignored — retry with --no-packignore and the path as a positional arg before giving up.
5. If the user asked to bundle, run the bundle command after a successful preview.
6. If no output path is provided, write packx-bundle.md. Create parent dirs (mkdir -p) before writing into a subfolder.
7. After bundling, run ls -lh OUTPUT_PATH when a file was written.
8. If command syntax is uncertain or packx returns a usage error, run packx --help, then retry once.

## Worked examples (follow this shape exactly)
Example 1 — "bundle the TypeScript source":
